in West Virginia.

72
00:03:12,820 --> 00:03:16,520
And a $43 billion dollar deal with state-run
Sinopec

73
00:03:16,520 --> 00:03:19,510
to develop Alaska’s liquid natural gas industry

74
00:03:19,510 --> 00:03:23,069
that could create up to 12,000 American jobs.

75
00:03:23,069 --> 00:03:26,230
Ok, so the Boeing deal is fine.

76
00:03:26,230 --> 00:03:28,240
But I would be somewhat wary about

77
00:03:28,240 --> 00:03:30,459
the Alaska and West Virginia deals.

78
00:03:30,459 --> 00:03:33,080
It’s hard to say since we don’t know the
details,

79
00:03:33,080 --> 00:03:35,220
but in the past countries who have let China

80
00:03:35,220 --> 00:03:37,780
invest heavily in their natural resources,

81
00:03:37,780 --> 00:03:40,180
have had some problems.

82
00:03:40,180 --> 00:03:42,940
But the really big win was for US companies

83
00:03:42,940 --> 00:03:44,500
looking to invest in China.

84
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:52,000
China announced a new rule allow foreign companies to own 51% stakes in foreign ventures.

85
00:03:52,020 --> 00:03:55,440
I know, that doesn’t even sound very generous.

86
00:03:55,459 --> 00:03:56,459
But previously,

87
00:03:56,459 --> 00:03:59,069
no US company could own a controlling share

88
00:03:59,069 --> 00:04:01,709
in a US-China joint venture.

89
00:04:01,709 --> 00:04:03,310
Even though a Chinese company could

90
00:04:03,310 --> 00:04:05,599
inside the United States.

91
00:04:05,599 --> 00:04:08,980
So why is China more open to foreign investment
now?

92
00:04:08,980 --> 00:04:12,140
Is it because China is implementing meaningful
rule of law

93
00:04:12,140 --> 00:04:14,350
and wants to level the playing field?

94
00:04:14,350 --> 00:04:15,840
Haha, no.

95
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:18,609
It’s because China’s economy is slowing
down

96
00:04:18,609 --> 00:04:20,799
and they really need the money.

97
00:04:20,799 --> 00:04:22,270
Like when you swear you weren’t going

98
00:04:22,270 --> 00:04:24,060
to move back in with your parents,

99
00:04:24,060 --> 00:04:27,380
but rent is really high right now, you know?

100
00:04:27,380 --> 00:04:29,900
But still, it’s a win for US companies.

101
00:04:29,900 --> 00:04:31,480
At least for the ones that hope to become

102
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:33,590
the next Starbucks in China...

103
00:04:33,590 --> 00:04:36,310
and not the next Home Depot.

104
00:04:36,310 --> 00:04:37,520
As for North Korea,

105
00:04:37,520 --> 00:04:39,490
Trump and Xi were in agreement.

106
00:04:39,490 --> 00:04:45,630
"We agreed not to replicate failed approaches
of the past,

107
00:04:45,630 --> 00:04:46,630
and there were many.”

108
00:04:46,630 --> 00:04:49,230
In other words: Thanks Obama.

109
00:04:49,230 --> 00:04:50,470
And Hillary.

110
00:04:50,470 --> 00:04:52,620
The Trump administration has been pushing
China

111
00:04:52,620 --> 00:04:55,580
to put even tougher sanctions on North Korea,

112
00:04:55,580 --> 00:04:58,280
even going so far as to cut off all trade.

113
00:04:58,280 --> 00:05:00,780
But while Trump tweeted that Xi agreed to

114
00:05:00,780 --> 00:05:02,490
upping the sanctions,

115
00:05:02,490 --> 00:05:03,490
as of this recording,

116
00:05:03,490 --> 00:05:06,479
there’s been no official announcements.

117
00:05:06,479 --> 00:05:07,980
So for trade and North Korea,

118
00:05:07,980 --> 00:05:11,150
the Trump administration made some definite
progress.

119
00:05:11,150 --> 00:05:15,050
But one of the fair criticisms of Trump’s
China trip was that,

120
00:05:15,050 --> 00:05:16,380
like past presidents,

121
